Access a value from other rows like LAG() for previous row, LEAD() for next row, FIRST_VALUE() for first row,
LAST_VALUE() for last row
Note:-  1. ORDER BY clause is mandatory
        2. PARTITION BY clause is optional
        3. FRAME CLAUSE is not applicable for LEAD,LAG, optional for FIRST_VALUE , mandatory for LAST_VALUE

LEAD(EXPRESSION,OFFSET,DEFAULT VALUES) OVER (PARTITION BY <COL-A> ORDER BY <col-b>)

LEAD(sales,2,10) OVER ( PARTITION BY productid ORDER BY sales)

OFFSET :- OFFSET is optional Number of rows forward or backward from current row default =1)
DEFAULT VALUES :- records were not found forward or backward it will return default value
example :- LEAD(sales,2,10) OVER ( PARTITION BY productid ORDER BY orderdate)
2 indicates :- get 2nd forward record of sales 
10 :- if 2nd forward record is not available .. shows default value 10.

LEAD() LAG() are used for Time Series Analysis
The process of analyzing the data to understand patterns,trends and behaviours over time. 
YEAR-ON-YEAR YoY  or MONTH-ON-MONTH MoM

--Analyze the month-over-month performance by find the percentage change
--in sales between the current and prvious months
SELECT 
*,
Monthsum - PreviousMonth differce,
ROUND(CAST( (Monthsum - PreviousMonth) AS FLOAT)/PreviousMonth *100,2) DiferencePercentage
FROM
(
SELECT
MONTH(ORDERDATE) ordermonth,
SUM(sales) Monthsum,
LAG(SUM(sales)) OVER (ORDER BY MONTH(ORDERDATE)) PreviousMonth
FROM
Sales.Orders
GROUP BY MONTH(OrderDate)
)t


--Time Gap Analysis
--Find the number o days between each oder and the previous order
SELECT
OrderID,
OrderDate currentorderdate,
LAG(orderdate) OVER(ORDER BY OrderDate) previousorderdate,
DATEDIFF(DAY,LAG(orderdate) OVER(ORDER BY OrderDate),OrderDate) DaysDifference
FROM 
Sales.Orders

FIRST_VALUE() & LAST_VALUE() ==>Syntax: FIRST_VALUE(Sales) OVER( ORDER BY Month)
LAST_VALUE(Sales) OVER(ORDER BY MONTH)

